// Classify each scenario
// A: anomaly type + minimum isolation level
// B: anomaly type + minimum isolation level
// C: anomaly type + minimum isolation level
// D: anomaly type + minimum isolation level

exercises.expected_solution:
// A: NON-REPEATABLE READ
// Transaction A reads the same row twice with different results in the SAME transaction.
// Minimum isolation: REPEATABLE_READ
// (READ_COMMITTED allows this: committed changes by other transactions become visible)

// B: DIRTY READ
// Transaction A reads Transaction B's uncommitted changes.
// If B rolls back, A made decisions on data that never existed.
// Minimum isolation: READ_COMMITTED
// (READ_UNCOMMITTED allows dirty reads; READ_COMMITTED prevents them)
// Note: PostgreSQL default (READ_COMMITTED) already prevents this.

// C: PHANTOM READ
// Same query returns different number of rows due to new rows inserted by other transactions.
// Transaction A's result set changes within the same transaction.
// Minimum isolation: SERIALIZABLE
// (REPEATABLE_READ prevents non-repeatable reads on EXISTING rows but not new rows)

// D: DIRTY READ (same as B)
// Reading uncommitted data from another transaction.
// Minimum isolation: READ_COMMITTED

public class IsolationAnalysis {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("A: Non-repeatable read → REPEATABLE_READ");
        System.out.println("B: Dirty read → READ_COMMITTED");
        System.out.println("C: Phantom read → SERIALIZABLE");
        System.out.println("D: Dirty read → READ_COMMITTED");
    }
}

